</tr>

<tr>
<td style=""><strong>Step 5: <br></strong>You can use a non-scented, household chlorine bleach that contains a chlorine compound to disinfect water. (Remember, 1/8 teaspoon and 8 drops are about the same quantity.)</td>
<td style="" align="center"><img src="/aboutow/ogwdw/images/emerg_image5.jpg" id="||CPIMAGE:90014|" alt="Image of non-scented, household chlorine bleach." title="7 Steps to Emergency Disinfection, Image 05" border="0" height="97" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="97"></td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td style=""><strong>Step 6: </strong><br>You can use tincture of iodine to disinfect filtered and settled water. Common household iodine from the medicine chest or first aid kit may be used to disinfect water.</td>
<td style="" align="center"><img src="/aboutow/ogwdw/images/emerg_image6.jpg" id="||CPIMAGE:90015|" alt="Image of tincture of iodine." title="7 Steps to Emergency Disinfection, Image 06" border="0" height="97" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="97"></td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td style=""><strong>Step 7: </strong><br>Tincture of iodine. For cloudy water add ten drops and let the solution stand for at least 30 minutes.</td>
<td style="" align="center"><img src="/aboutow/ogwdw/images/emerg_image7.jpg" id="||CPIMAGE:90016|" alt="Image showing the application of tincture of iodine to cloudy water." title="7 Steps to Emergency Disinfection, Image 07" border="0" height="97" hspace="0" vspace="0" width="97"></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></p>
			</div>
			
		</div>
	
</div>
